Germany: a costly budget fetish
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It was in fact Germany that insisted on incorporating this principle into the criteria outlined in the Maastricht Treaty, which set the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a change in the political regime.
Thus, the independence of the French National Bank during the ratification referendum on the Maastricht Treaty in 1992 was one of the strongest arguments of the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, on the contrary, it has become commonplace, one might say, to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schaüble, has been regularly commenting on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the central bank's independence.
If he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price norm," in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nonetheless provides his advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should handle them in order to achieve such a goal.
There are precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Finance Minister of Germany, gave his well-intentioned advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was ultimately to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typically Dutch laconicism, replied that it was nothing out of place for a politician to express his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Yet," he added, "it would be entirely abnormal to take account of [his] suggestions."
Please provide the sentence you would like translated from French to English.
Respecting the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of the German "Stabilitätskultur" ("culture of stability").
The founding act that established the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal in 1956 to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's entreaties, which called upon it to contain the rise in interest rates.
At that time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France that reported to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following the various crises that have shaken the EUM, monetary policy is increasingly replacing fiscal policy.
Would the old dogma have become obsolete?
Europe remains very vulnerable; the average resident of the EU has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming is that we are close to a critical situation.
Yet the United States do better.
Despite facing a difficult political deadlock to manage, they managed to address the macroeconomic problem (weak aggregate demand) they were encountering by implementing expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which were initially far more severe than in Europe.
(There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.)
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the more capable they are of fulfilling their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of support from the population.
Indeed, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, notably in Germany, calling for greater pressure to be applied to it.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's independence lies in the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, allowing the economy to sink into stagnation, or worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression toward nationalism, both on the right and the left, in all countries of the European Union, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical consequence of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance, with its obsession with the "schwarze Null," the budget balance, against all winds and tides.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably not only from an arithmetic perspective but also from a moral standpoint, even though this goes against economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the leading German specialists in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures must, on average, be financed by current revenues.
Public spending, and the resources it requires, are justified by their usefulness.
This means that investments aimed at improving productivity – equipment expenditures – can be financed through debt, whose service is ensured by the growth of revenues and the base of related income.
This classical approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is always practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
It is crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment spending is managed at this level (a proportion that has been declining, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenses are consistent with supporting the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (Mittelstand).
However, compared to the beginning of the 1990s and at constant prices, investment spending has decreased by about 15%.
More than a decade ago, they were insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not the way to prepare for the future, it is the way to undermine productivity and prosperity.
In short, the schwarze Null goes against the intended goal.
The outdated infrastructure (certainly not as much as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
In addition, the fiscal restraint of German leaders extends beyond German borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to accommodate national particularities.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But to make the only institution willing to "do what it takes" to bring the ECU back on track a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
That states use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain degree of flexibility in this regard.
